Topic5: File Permissions:
-------------------------
Linux file permissions control who can read, write, or execute a file or directory
These permission are crucial for system security and user management

Types of permissions & Users
----------------------------
Three Types of permissions:

	.Read(r): View contents of a file/directory
	.Write(w): Modify file or add/remove in directory
	.Execute(x): Run file (script/program) or access directory

Three Types of Users:

	.Owner(user): who created the file/owner of the file
	.Group: User in files group
	.Others: All other users not a owner or not in group

Permission Format:
------------------	
use ls -l to see permission (E.g., -rwxrw-r--)

Breakdown: (-rwxrw-r--)

Symbol			Meaning
-				Regular file (d for directory)
rwx				Owner: read, write, Execute
rw-				Group: read, write, No permission
r--				Others: read, No permission, No permission

Numeri(Octal) Notation:
-----------------------
Each permission had a value:

	. r=4
	. w=2
	. x=1    Total value is '7'

To set permissions: "chmod 755 filename"

	Owner: rwx(7=4+2+1)
	Group: r-x(5=4+0+1)
	Others:r-x(5=4+0+1)
	
	Full permission: 777
	Zero permission: 000

Symbolic	Numeric	Permissions
,---	0	None
,--x	1	Execute
,-w-	2	Write
,-wx	3	Write+Execute
r--	4	Read
r-x	5	read+Execute
rw-	6	read+write
rwx	7	read+write+Execute

Changing Permission and Ownership:
---------------------------------
View permission: "ls -ls"
Change permission: "chmod [options] [permission] file"
Change Owner: chown user file


Topic:6
-------
$: This is normal user with limited permissions
#: Super user/root user with all permissions

To convert normal user to super/root user: "sudo su"

Topic:7 copy, move or rename files and directories
---------------------------------------------------
1.copy commands(cp)
	.cp raju shiva
	
2.copy file to directory
	.cp shiva /path/to/dir
	.cp shiva /home/ec2-user/nexgen
	
3.copy Multiple files
	.cp dinesh naresh raju /home/ec2-user/nexgen
	
4.Move a file
	.mv shiva /home/ec2-user/nexgen

5.Move a directory
	.mv nexgen /home/ec2-user/yash/priya

6.Rename commands(mv)
Linux does not have a separate rename command; mv is used for renaming

rename a file:
	.mv oldname newname
	
remove a directory(old)	

Topic:8 Reporting File system disk space usage
----------------------------------------------
Learn how to check disk and memory usage easily on linux

Disk space usage commands:
	.df -h : Report file system disk space usage (human readable)
	.du -h : Estimate file space usage(human readable)
	
Memory Usage Commands:
	.free : Display amount of free and used memory in the system
	.free -h : Human readable memory output
	.free -k : Display memory in kilobytes(KB)
	.free -m : Display memory usage in megabytes(MB)
	.free -g : Display memory usage in gigabytes(GB)
